Political leaders in Uasin Gishu snubbed a peace forum organised by the NCIC in Eldoret on Friday, sparking off protests from elders in the region.Kalenjin Elders&rsquo; Council chairman Major (Rtd) John Seii said some politicians had been engaging in hate speech and incitement and should have attended the peace forum.He said they were angry that none of the politicians turned up for the important forum, yet they had been invited.&ldquo;It&rsquo;s as if they don&rsquo;t value peace, yet they know the challenges our county has been going through,&rdquo; Seii said.Kaparo cautioned Uasin Gishu Governor Jackson Mandago (pictured), his rival Bundotich Kiprop, alias Buzeki, and other leaders in Uasin Gishu to stop playing tribal politics and using inflammatory remarks during campaigns.NCIC chairman Francis ole Kaparo said all political leaders in the region will be monitored by the commission throughout the campaign period. &ldquo;I want to ask Mandago and other leaders to tone town on inflammatory statements,&rdquo; he said.Kaparo said the leaders must allow residents to exercise their democratic right by voting for anyone they wish to back. Uasin Gishu is among counties classified as hotspots ahead of the August 8 polls.Kaparo said the commission will be closely monitoring election campaigns in the region, particularly in Turbo constituency, where he said there have been incidents of tribal politics.He said some politicians involved in hate speech and incitement in Uasin Gishu and other parts of the country are being investigated and may be taken to court.